								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">24</div> <div class="vers-content">oculum pro oculo, dentem pro dente, manum pro manu, pedem pro pede,</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">24</div> <div class="vers-content">Eye for eye, tooth for tooth, hand for hand, foot for foot,</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">24</div> <div class="vers-content">So it is to be; an eye for an eye, a tooth for a tooth,  a hand for a hand, a foot for a foot;</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">25</div> <div class="vers-content">adustionem pro adustione, vulnus pro vulnere, livorem pro livore.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">25</div> <div class="vers-content">Burning for burning, wound for wound, stripe for stripe.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">25</div> <div class="vers-content">burning for burning, wound for wound, bruise for bruise.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">26</div> <div class="vers-content">Si percusserit quispiam oculum servi sui aut ancillÃ¦, et luscos eos fecerit, dimittet eos liberos pro oculo quem eruit.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">26</div> <div class="vers-content">If any man strike the eye of his manservant or maidservant, and leave them but one eye, he shall let them go free for the eye which he put out.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">26</div> <div class="vers-content">If anyone gives servant or handmaid a blow on the eye, so that the sight of it is lost, he must set them free in return for the sight he robbed them of;</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">27</div> <div class="vers-content">Dentem quoque si excusserit servo vel ancillÃ¦ suÃ¦, similiter dimittet eos liberos.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">27</div> <div class="vers-content">Also if he strike out a tooth of his manservant or maidservant, he shall in like manner make them free.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">27</div> <div class="vers-content">or if he knocks out a tooth, he must let servant or handmaid go free by the same title.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">28</div> <div class="vers-content">Si bos cornu percusserit virum aut mulierem, et mortui fuerint, lapidibus obruetur: et non comedentur carnes ejus, dominus quoque bovis innocens erit.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">28</div> <div class="vers-content">If an ox gore a man or a woman, and they die, he shall be stoned: and his flesh shall not be eaten, but the owner of the ox shall be quit.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">28</div> <div class="vers-content">If an ox gores a man or woman to death, it shall be stoned, and the flesh of it is not to be eaten. But the owner of the ox shall be held innocent,</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">29</div> <div class="vers-content">Quod si bos cornupeta fuerit ab heri et nudiustertius, et contestati sunt dominum ejus, nec recluserit eum, occideritque virum aut mulierem: et bos lapidibus obruetur, et dominum ejus occident.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">29</div> <div class="vers-content">But if the ox was wont to push with his horn yesterday and the day before, and they warned his master, and he did not shut him up, and he shall kill a man or a woman: then the ox shall be stoned, and his owner also shall be put to death.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">29</div> <div class="vers-content">unless the ox has been using its horns for some time past, and he has refused to shut it away when appeal was made to him. Then, if the ox gores man or woman, it shall be stoned, and he too shall be put to death,</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">30</div> <div class="vers-content">Quod si pretium fuerit ei impositum, dabit pro anima sua quidquid fuerit postulatus.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">30</div> <div class="vers-content">And if they set a price upon him, he shall give for his life whatsoever is laid upon him.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">30</div> <div class="vers-content">unless a fine is imposed on him instead; if so, he shall pay whatever ransom is demanded for his life.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">31</div> <div class="vers-content">Filium quoque et filiam si cornu percusserit, simili sententiÃ¦ subjacebit.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">31</div> <div class="vers-content">If he have gored a son, or a daughter, he shall fall under the like sentence.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">31</div> <div class="vers-content">The parents shall have the same claim upon him, whether it be a son or daughter of theirs the ox has gored;</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">32</div> <div class="vers-content">Si servum ancillamque invaserit, triginta siclos argenti domino dabit, bos vero lapidibus opprimetur.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">32</div> <div class="vers-content">If he assault a bondman or bondwoman, he shall give thirty sicles of silver to their master, and the ox shall be stoned.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">32</div> <div class="vers-content">if it has attacked man-servant or woman-servant, the owner must pay thirty silver pieces, and the ox must be stoned.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">33</div> <div class="vers-content">Si quis aperuerit cisternam, et foderit, et non operuerit eam, cecideritque bos aut asinus in eam,</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">33</div> <div class="vers-content">If a man open a pit, and dig one, and cover it not, and an ox or an ass fall into it,</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">33</div> <div class="vers-content">If a man who has opened an old well, or is digging a new one, does not cover it up, and ox or ass falls into it,</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">34</div> <div class="vers-content">reddet dominus cisternÃ¦ pretium jumentorum: quod autem mortuum est, ipsius erit.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">34</div> <div class="vers-content">The owner of the pit shall pay the price of the beasts: and that which is dead shall be his own.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">34</div> <div class="vers-content">the owner of the well shall pay the full value of the beasts; the carcase he may keep for himself.</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">35</div> <div class="vers-content">Si bos alienus bovem alterius vulneraverit, et ille mortuus fuerit: vendent bovem vivum, et divident pretium, cadaver autem mortui inter se dispertient.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">35</div> <div class="vers-content">If one manâ€™s ox gore another manâ€™s ox, and he die: they shall sell the live ox, and shall divide the price, and the carcass of that which died they shall part between them:</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">35</div> <div class="vers-content">If one manâ€™s ox is wounded by anotherâ€™s, and dies of it, they shall sell the live ox and share the price of it, dividing the carcase of the dead ox between them;</div></div></td>
								</tr><tr>									<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">36</div> <div class="vers-content">Sin autem sciebat quod bos cornupeta esset ab heri et nudiustertius, et non custodivit eum dominus suus: reddet bovem pro bove, et cadaver integrum accipiet.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">36</div> <div class="vers-content">But if he knew that his ox was wont to push yesterday and the day before, and his master did not keep him in: he shall pay ox for ox, and shall take the whole carcass.</div></div></td>
																	<td><div class="vers"><div class="vers-no">36</div> <div class="vers-content">unless it has been known for some time past that the live ox was using its horns, and the owner has not kept it under control. If so, he shall restore ox for ox, and keep the whole carcase for himself.</div></div></td>
								</tr>					</tbody>
				</table>
